Python Character Set: 
 It is a set of valid characters acceptable by a programming language in scripting. 

i)   Alphabets       : All capital (A-Z) and small (a-z) alphabets.
ii)  Digits          : All digits 0-9.
iii) Special Symbols : All kind of special symbols like, ” ‘ l ; : ! ~ @ # $ % ^ ` & * ( ) _ + – = { } [ ] \ .
iv)  Spaces          : All white spaces like tab space, blank space, newline, and carriage return.
v)   Others          : All ASCII and UNICODE characters are supported by python.


# Code - First Program
i)
print("Hello")

- O/P.: 
Hello



Comments:

1) Single line comment:
    Write "#" at the start of the line.

2) Multi line comment:
    Write "#" at the start of each line. 
    or 
    Write ''' / """ at the start and ''' / """ at the end.



Seperator and End:
 Default seperator is "space".
 Default end is "Next Line (\n)".

# Code - Seperator and End
i)
print("Hello", "World")
print("Hello", "World ", sep=" , ", end="End")          # Seperate each object with ","

- O/P.: 
Hello World
Hello , World End



Escape Characters:
 To insert a character that cannot be directly used in a string. Write "\" followed by the character that needs to be added.

i)    \' and \"        : Single quote / Double quote	
ii)   \\	              : Backslash	
iii)  \n	              : New Line	
iv)   \r	              : Carriage Return	
v)    \t	              : Tab	
vi)   \b	              : Backspace	
vii)  \f	              : Form Feed	
viii) \1 (octal value) : Octal value	
ix)   \x (hex value)	  : Hex value


# Code - Escape Characters
i) 
print("I am \'Student\' and I am learning \"Python\".")

- O/P.:
I am 'Student' and I am learning "Python".


ii) 
print("I am Student. \n and \rI am learning \t Python.\b ")

- O/P.:
I am Student. 
I am learning    Python


iii) 
print("\110\145\154\154\157 \x57\x6f\x72\x6c\x64")          # Octal and Hex Values

- O/P.: 
Hello World

